<TITLE>HAWAII'S SEARCH FOR SOVEREIGNTY</TITLE>
<H1>HAWAII'S SEARCH FOR SOVEREIGNTY</H1>
<H2>In the Aloha State, a self-determination movement gains strength from diverse political groups</H2>
(Read article <A HREF="csm.html">text only</A> without images, or view <A HREF="csmgifs.html">images only</A> without text)
<P>
<IMG SRC="csm1.gif"><BR>
</CENTER><BLOCKQUOTE>RECLAIMING A HERITAGE: <EM>Members of the Ohana Council erected an ancient Hawaiian shrine on Makapuu Beach.  Known as the most radical of Hawaii's sovereignty groups, they also distributed leaflets encouraging non-Hawaiian tourists to leave the islands.</EM></BLOCKQUOTE><CENTER>
<P>
<H3>Hawaiian Sovereignty Groups Seek Recognition, Land</H3>
<STRONG>Christian Science Monitor, Monday, October 17, 1994</STRONG>
</CENTER>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>
By Daniel B. Wood, Staff writer of the Christian Science Monitor
<P>
OUT of 47 acres of rain forest above this rural seaside village, a group of kanaka maoli - native Hawaiians - are creating what they call the "rebirth of a nation."
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=Right SRC="csmplate.gif" VSPACE=2 HSPACE=5><HR>SAY IT WITH A LICENSE PLATE: <EM>Some Hawaiians use their cars to display their political leanings.  the Ohana Council has issued 'Independent Nation State of Hawaii' driver's licenses.</EM>
<HR>
<P>
Gravel paths lead to and from canvas-covered decks and geodesic dome tents. Blue and yellow outhouses dot the perimeter of freshly planted taro patches. While chickens cluck and finches flit, chain saws and earth movers clear a view of white water reefs below.
