<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WDCGG - GLOBAL ATMOSPHERIC WATCH
</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY>
<H1>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
THE WMO GLOBAL ATMOSPHERE WATCH (GAW) SYSTEM
</P></H1>
<HR SIZE="5">
Extract from "Status of the WMO Global Atmosphere Watch Programme as at 31 December 1993", WMO/TD-NO. 636.
<PRE>

<DL>
<DT><B><H2>Introduction</H2></B>

<DD>1.1      The issues of global change and man's influence on the quality of the natural environment are complex.
Global warning is expected if observed increases in the concentrations of man-made greenhouse gases (CH4, CO2, N2O,
CFCs, and ozone) and alterations in the amounts of clouds and particles in the atmosphere continue; the stratospheric
ozone layer, and, consequently, the surface solar flux of ultraviolet radiation are being modified; there are changes
in the integrated oxidation rate or oxidizing capacity of the atmosphere, and perturbations in the abundance of tropospheric
trace gases, in particular ozone.

<DD>1.2      Assessing and understanding these changes and the responses of the global environment to them occupy a prominent
position on the international scientific agenda today.   Finding ecologically effective and economically efficient
solutions to the resulting problems confronts all countries of the world with a challenge of global dimensions.

<DD>1.3      The scientific input to the debate on environmental issues must be on adequate knowledge.   The latter can only be
achieved through high-quality, strategically oriented observations and research related to the particular issues.
Hence the establishment of proper global environmental observation systems as the only effective way to ensure systematic
gathering of data worldwide, with comparable and clearly defined measuring criteria, co-ordinated data processing and
quality assurance, and the distribution and provision of available information to the widely varied group of users.
This complex international task must be tackled jointly by countries, international organizations and the scientific community.


<DD>1.4      The Global Atmosphere Watch (GAW) programme of the World Meteorological Organization (WMO) contributes to this purpose.



<DT><B><H2>Establishment and implementation</H2></B>

<DD>1.5      The GAW was establishes in 1989 from the integration of WMO activities involving the chemical composition and
related physical characteristics of the atmosphere and the meteorological aspects of air pollution monitoring which existed
under the Organization's Global Ozone Observing System (GO3OS) established in the 1950s and Background Air Pollution
Monitoring Network (BAPMoN) started in the 1960s.

<DD>1.6      Considerations which  led to the establishment of GAW included :

         (i)    the concern which had arisen regarding the quality, timeliness and completeness of many of the BAPMoN and
                GO3OS data;

         (ii)   the need to expand and strengthen WMO's and Members' research and monitoring activities which would focus on
                cognizant scientific issues.   At present, such issues include, (a) at the global level; climate change,
                stratospheric ozone depletion, tropospheric ozone increase and changes in the oxidizing capacity of the
                atmosphere; and (b) at the regional level: acidic wet and dry deposition, the long-range transport of
                pollutants,biogeochemical cycles, exchange of pollutants between the atmosphere and the sea, biomass burning,
                biogenic sources and sinks of greenhouse gases and others:

         (iii)  the need to strengthen the role of WMO and the Meteorological Services of WMO Member countries in the field of
                atmospheric composition assessment, early warning and research, in the light of growing requirements of
                atmospheric environmental information;

         (iv)   the need for Meteorological Services of Members to ensure that atmospheric composition measurements become an
                integral part of atmospheric observations in general and are carried out with the same attention as is given to
                the measurements of other meteorological parameters;

         (v)    the need to expand collaboration and promote involvement with other relevant programmes (e.g. International Global
                Atmospheric Chemistry Project (IGAC), International Geosphere/Biosphere Programme, Global Climate Observing System
                (GCOS), Global Ocean Observing System (GOOS), Global Terrestrial Observing System(GTOS)).


<DD>1.7      GAW activities are implemented in accordance with WMO Technical Regulations (Reference 1).



<DT><B><H2>Objectives</H2></B>

<DD>1.8      The GAW pursues two main objectives, namely:

         (a)   to serve an early warning and forecasting system for changes in the background chemical composition and related
               physical characteristics of the atmosphere which have direct or indirect effects on climate, ultra violet-B
               radiation, the ozone layer, the oxidizing capacity of the atmosphere and terrestrial and marine ecosystems;

         (b)   to document, detect and understand such changes.



<DT><B><H2>Activities</H2></B>

<DD>1.9      GAW activities include measurements at participating stations; chemical analysis of samples at participating
laboratories; co-ordinated quality assurance programme; data archiving and publication; capacity building through training and
technical co-operation; and monitoring of the operation of the system.

<DD>1.10     (omission)



<DT><B><H2>Current regulations, procedures, practices and arrangements

Measurements
</H2></B>

<DT><I><B>Categories of stations</B></I>

<DD>1.11     There are two categories of manned GAW stations, namely global and regional stations.

<DD>1.11.1   Global stations were formerly called "baseline" stations.   They are established to provide measurements needed to
address atmospheric environmental issues of global scale and importance, currently those given in paragraph 1.6 (ii) (a) above.

<DD>1.11.2   Regional stations were formerly known as "regional stations", "continental stations" and/or "regional stations with
extended programmes".   They are established to provide measurements primarily to help assess regional aspects of global
atmospheric environmental issues and atmospheric environmental problems in various regions or countries, in particular those
listed in paragraph 1.6 (ii) (b) above.

<DD>1.11.3   Countries operating stations under other global, regional or national programmes which might be to interest to GAW are
encouraged to offer their data for inclusion in the growing GAW data pool.   Examples of such "contributing" stations from which
GAW currently benefits are stations belonging to the EMEP (CO-operative Programme for Monitoring and Evaluation of the Long-Range
Transmission of Air Pollution in Europe).

<DD>1.11.4   Efforts are also continuing to step up co-operation between GAW and the WHO programme on urban and industrial air
pollution monitoring.


<DT><H2><I><B>Network density</B></I></H2>

<DD>1.12     It is currently considered that the required number of global stations should be such that a minimum of one per
principal climatic zone and per major biome is achieved.

<DD>1.13     As for regional stations, their number should allow regional aspects of global environmental issues and environmental
problems of interest to the region or country(ies) concerned to be adequately addressed.


<DT><H2><I><B>Criteria for siting stations</B></I></H2>

<DD>1.14     Despite the difficulty of finding locations where suitable conditions are met often enough and evenly enough through
the year and on a long-term basis, siting criteria have been determined for GAW stations.

         In principle, and depending on the measurement component:

         (a)   global station should be preferably located in remote (if possible pristine) areas where:

              (i)    no significant changes in land-use practices are expected for at least 50 years within a reasonable distance
                     (30-50 km) in all directions from the stations; away from major populations and industrial centres, away from
                     major highways and airports; if possible on islands, mountain ranges and major forest reserves;

              (ii)   effects of natural phenomena such as volcanic eruptions, forest fires and dust storms are not frequently
                     experienced;

              (iii)  it can be reasonably assumed that the ambient air at the station is entirely free of the influence of local
                     pollution sources, nearly free of the influence of regional pollution sources ar least 60% of the time evenly
                     distributed over the year, and contains only diluted vestiges of chemical components carried to the site by
                     the long-range transport from sources located at least 30-50 kilometres away;

              (iv)   a full programme of surface meteorological observations is carried out and an upper air station is not
                     farther away than 50-70 km.

        (b) regional stations should be located:

              (i)    preferably in rural areas, at any rate sufficiently far away from population and industrial centres,
                     so that the effect of local sources of air pollution is absent at the station most of the year;

              (ii)   on, or close to meteorological/climatological stations making surface and rawindsonde observations.

<DD>1.15     Other criteria of prospective measurements include: availability and interest of scientists, existence of a suitable
infrastructure, relevance to national and/or regional issues (especially in developing countries).



<DT><H2><I><B>Measurement programme</B></I></H2>

<DD>1.16     GAW global stations are considered as research centres and expected to monitor all or most of the variables listed in
paragraph 1.18 below.

<DD>1.17     Regional stations have a more flexible, less intensive, observational programme, which should include as many or few of
the parameters listed in paragraph 1.18 below and/or others as the needs of the region/country dictate.

<DD>1.18     The recommended GAW measurement programme includes the following components:

         (a) chemical composition of rainfall and snow;

         (b) atmospheric gases, including;

               (i)    greenhouse gases - carbon dioxide; the chlorofluorocarbon, their substitutes, intermediates and final
                      products; methane; nitrous oxide; tropospheric ozone; water vapour

               (ii)   ozone - surface, total column, vertical profile and precursor gases, using ground-based instruments
                      such as spectrophotometers, sondes, lasers, microwaves, as well as satellites;

               (iii)  reactive gas species such as: sulphur dioxide and the reduced sulphur species; nitrogen oxides and the
                      reduced nitrogen species; carbon monoxide;

        (c)  aerosols and optical depth or transparency of the atmosphere, including:

               (i)    total concentrations and physical and chemical characteristics of particles, including mineral aerosols
                      and their vertical profiles;

               (ii)   turbidity, total optical depth, visibility

        (d)  solar radiation including UV-B;

        (e)  radionuclides, including krypton-85, radon, tritium, and the isotopic composition of selected substances.

<DD>1.19     At the time of writing this report (October 1994), QA protocols and manuals were in preparation or planned for each of
the above measurements.



<DT><B><H2>Sampling and chemical analysis</H2></B>

<DD>1.20     The chemical analysis of samples (precipitation water, air filters, flasks, etc.) obtained at GAW stations are normally
carried out at chemical laboratories located in the relevant participating countries.   Recommended laboratory and sample
collection methods for precipitation chemistry are described in References 5.   Each participating country is therefore encouraged
to arrange for the samples from its station(s) to be analyzed in a chemical laboratory within the country.   Such arrangements are
normally made prior to the start of measurements.


<DT><B><H2>Data

Reporting, archiving and publication
</H2></B>

<DD>1.21     GAW data nave been and are currently reported, archived and published as follows.

<DD>1.21.1   The agency operating the station(s) in each participating country submits all the data from the station(s) on data
reporting forms or preferably magnetic tapes/cassettes of agreed of formats to the appropriate data centre.


             <B>Data Centre                                                Data type</B>

            (a) World Ozone and UV Data Centre                             Ozone and UV radiation
                Atmospheric Environment Service (AES)
                4905 Dufferin Street
                Downsview, Ontario
                Canada M3H 5T4
                Tel: 416 739 4635
                Fax: 416 739 4281
                Contact: Edward W. Hare

            (b) National Climatic Data Center (NCDC)                       Turbidity
                Federal Building
                Asheville, North Carolia 28801
                USA
                Fax: 704 271 4328
                Contact: Arthur G. DeCotiis

            (c) WMO World Data Centre for                                  Greenhouse and other
                Greenhouse Gases (WDCGG)                                   atmospheric gases, except
                Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA)                          ozone
                1-3-4 Otemachi, Chiyoda-ku
                Tokyo 100
                Japan

            (d) World Data Centre for Aerosols (WDCA)                      Aerosols
                Atmospheric Physics Unit
                Environment Institute
                Joint Research Centre
                Commission of the European Communities
                Ispra Establishment
                1-21020 Ispra (Varese)
                Italy

            (e) World Radiation Centre (WRC)                               Solar Radiation, excluding UV
                Voeikov Main Geophysical Observatory
                Karbyshev Str. 7
                194018 St. Petersburg
                Russia
                Fax: 7812 247 0163
                Contact: Anatoly Tsvetkov

<DD>1.21.3   Every two months, the Centre at AES in Canada processes all ozone data (surface, total column, vertical distribution)
and publishes GAW Data Volume III: "Ozone Data for World (ODW)".   The Centre also publishes an "Index" which contains the list
of stations, a station catalogue with information on stations (names, organizations operating the stations, types of observation,
types of instruments used, observation programmes) as well as a catalogue of available ozone data (stations, period, data type,
OWD volume numbers in which the data are contained);

<DD>1.21.4   The Centre at NCDC extracts, processes and prepares for publication the turbidity data.   Data for the years through 1992
have been published in "Global Atmosphere Background Monitoring for Selected Environmental Parameters, BAPMoN Data for (year),
Volume I - Atmospheric Aerosol Optical Depth".   The data of the years 1972 through 1980 were published by the Centre and those of
the years since 1981 are published by the WMO Secretariat.

<DD>1.21.5   The WDCGG at JMA started operations on 1 October 1990.   As described more fully in Reference 6, the WDCGG collects
hourly, daily, monthly and event observations of all trace gases, except ozone; applies procedures for quality control, assessment,
processing and interpretation to the data; publishes a "data report", GAW Data Volume IV, every six months; prepares a "data
summary" every six months; and prepares and publishes a "data catalogue" every two years.   To date (September 1994) the following
titles have been issued:

         WDCGG publication No.:

         1. Data Reporting Manual

         2. Data Report (covering the data period 1967 through August 1992)

         3. Data Report (data received during the period September 1992 through March 1993)

         4. Data Catalogue containing information on the methods of measurements, 

         5. Data Report

         6. CD-ROM containing all data available up to that point in time.

<DD>1.21.6   Until, after many years of dedicated, crucial and much appreciated services, the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)
discontinued its involvement in GAW-related activities in October 1993, unprocessed data of precipitation chemistry and suspended
particulate matter used to be forwarded from the Centre ar NCDC to the then "WMO Collaborating Centre for Background Air Pollution
Data" which EPA had established in Research Triangle Park, North Carolina, USA, most recently within their Analysis and Research
Branch, Atmospheric Research and Exposure Assessment Laboratory.   The WMO Collaborating centre would process, publish (or prepare
for publication) and archive both types of data.   Thus GAW data of precipitation chemistry and suspended particulate matter
through 1984 have been published in GAW Data Volume II which, until then, was entitled continuous atmospheric carbon dioxide and
suspended particulate matter".

<DD>1.21.7   Since October 1993 WMO has been working on arrangements for a replacement centre for precipitation chemistry elsewhere in
North America.

<DD>1.21.8   The WDCA has begun to collect data from GAW station worldwide.   The stations which will be include and the exact details
of the measurements, frequencies of measurements, reporting procedures and other operational aspects are currently being
determined.



<DT><B><H2>Availability</H2></B>

<DD>1.22     Details on GAW data availability on paper, magnetic tapes/diskettes and CD-ROM, as applicable, including conditions and
procedures for ordering, can be obtained directly from the active Centres indicated in paragraph 1.21.2 above.   Copies of
published GAW Data Volumes I, II and IV, subject to availability in stock, can be obtained upon request from the WMO Secretariat.



<DT><B><H2>Quality assurance</H2></B>

<DD>1.23     Data Quality assurance (QA) activities in GAW are at present in the conception/development stage.   In the past, WMO
atmospheric composition activities concentrated on the promotion of measurements, especially for regional stations, and a small
group of investigators from developed countries were, to one degree or another, left to arrange for a QA programme to ensure data
quality for measurements from their countries.   This is true of CO2 measurements, O3 reactive gases, aerosol chemistry and solar
radiation.

<DD>1.24     With the establishment of GAW, WMO has undertaken to strengthen existing quality assurance (QA) programmes and to
implement new ones for measurements not yet covered under a unified QA approach called for in the relevant Technical Regulations.
The GAW QA programme involves the establishment of three Quality Assurance/Science Activity Centres (QA/SACs) in Germany, USA and
Japan, and its goal is to provide a clear, workable structure that will:

         -   deliver quality assured data to the GAW Data Centres, in accordance with defined data quality objectives (DQOs) and
             standard operating procedures (SOPs) as stated in the appropriate Quality Assurance Project Plans (QAPjP):

         -   provide uniform DQOs and clearly defined procedures for data management;

         -   maintain and, where necessary, improve the quality of data by performing management functions that include:

                  training of scientific personnel
                  training of station operating personnel
                  holding of workshops on SOPs, Quality Control (QC) techniques, recurring problems, etc.;
                  design of QC, calibrations, intercomparisons and experiments to prevent and/or resolve problems.

<DD>1.25     under the QA/SACs, GAW QA management will be structured so as to ensure:

         -   station and programme audits
         -   rapid feedback of QA reports and reviews and of QC experiment results that identify the nature of operating problems
             to the personnel operating the stations;
         -   feedback of descriptions of end use and value of data to the GAW sites; and
         -   regular peer reviews of GAW procedures and data, including expert consultations to resolve apparent problems.

<DD>1.26     The proposed overall management structure for GAW QA practically exists.   However, it needs to be focused on a
three-level hierarchy, i.e. local (station), regional and global, with co-ordination by the WMO Secretariat, as sketched.

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER="10">
<TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="QAImplementation.gif">
</TD></TR></TABLE>
</CENTER>


<DD>1.27     At the global level, on the advice of the EC Panel of Experts on Atmospheric Chemistry and Environmental Pollution, an
ad-hoc Steering Committee will be designated to oversee QA/SAC activities in order to balance the interests of various GAW data
producers, quality assurance officers, central data and flag archivers, users of the data, and international experts.

<DD>1.28     At the local level, the GAW stations will collect the data in accordance with the GAW DQOs and SOPs and transmit the data,
proposed data flags, and the stations' QC reports to the QA/Science Centres for their regional areas.   This level is the only at
which data changes will be made.

<DD>1.29     At the regional level, the QA/SACs will be the major scientific institutes responsible on a geographical area basis for
QA of all GAW data from the relevant sites.   The Centres will preferably be based at GAW global stations or laboratories.   The
three geographical regions suggested for QA/Science Centres are:

         -   Europe and Africa (WMO Regions VI and I)
         -   The Americas (WMO Region III and IV)
         -   Asia (WMO Region II and V)

<DD>1.30     The GAW QA/SACs will be responsible for critically reviewing and accepting the QA flags to the station data, identifying
and resolving quality performance differences among the stations of their geographical region, giving their station' data and QC
reports a timely review and notifying the stations immediately of any performance problems which are detected.

<DD>1.31     The QA/SACs will also provide reference materials to sites, design QC experiments and expert consultations to resolve
problems and organize training, instrument calibrations and intercomparisons, and workshops.   For more details on QA in GAW see
Reference 7, 8 and 9.



<DT><B><H2>Capacity building</H2></B>

<DD>1.32     To ensure that the developing countries realize the full benefits of GAW and are full partners in addressing the
scientific and environmental policy challenges facing the global community, training courses on background atmospheric composition
measurements are held at appropriate times and a global education and training programme in atmospheric chemistry is currently
under development.


<DT><H2><I><B>Training courses on background atmospheric composition measurements</B></I></H2>

<DD>1.33     Within the framework of the WMO Global Atmosphere Watch (GAW), the objectives of the courses are to train meteorological
personnel - mainly from developing countries - engaged or preparing to engage in scientific and managerial work at or in relation
to GAW regional stations.

<DD>1.34     The successful trainees are expected, after the courses, to be qualified to carry out the following duties in their home
countries:

         (a) supervision of observers who in turn are responsible for the operation of the instruments used to make the
             observations, the preparation of the final data products from the instrument readings, the application of quality
             control to the data, the timely reporting of the data to the appropriate GAW data centres and their archiving within
             the country;

         (b) supervision of instrument technicians trained for the testing, calibration, first line maintenance and repair of the
             instruments;

         (c) liaison with the chemical laboratory where the samples collected at the station(s) are analyzed;

         (d) interpretation of GAW data and other information and their applications to the solution of atmospheric environment
             problems of concern to the country;

         (e) scientific and technical aspects of the work of the station(s) at the national and international levels.


<DT><H2><I><B>Global education and training programme in atmospheric chemistry</B></I></H2>

<DD>1.35     Agenda 21 calls for new partnerships that cut across isolated compartments that many scientific communities and
organizations have long found comfortable.   The new "indigenous capacity building" programme in atmospheric chemistry is sponsored
by the Global Atmosphere Watch of WMO, the international Global Atmospheric Chemistry (IGAC) Project of the international
Geosphere/Biosphere Programme (IGBP), the Global Change System for Analysis, Research and Training (START) and the Education and
Training Division of the American Geophysical Union (AGU).   It sets out to organize an international team of volunteer scientists
to: (a) teach atmospheric chemistry in areas around the world where new GAW global stations are being established; (b) help
establish atmospheric chemistry programmes at universities and training centres in developing countries; and (c) work to establish
long-term co-operative arrangements with relevant academia, global research and monitoring programmes, and professional societies.
For more details, see Reference 9.
</DL>
</PRE>

