<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Quality Assurance / Science Activity Centre
</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><H2>Quality Assurance / Science Activity Centre
</H2></CENTER>
<HR>

<H3><B>Functions of a QA/SAC</B></H3>
<P>

The QA/SACs provide to WMO the communications and constructive assistance 
necessary for maintaining consistent and known data quality in the GAW Programme 
so that it can achieve its monitoring goals.   They are an essential and 
integral part of the GAW network and the operational mechanism for harmonization and 
coordination of GAW activities.   The approach shall be scientists helping 
scientists.
<P>

The QA/SACs will facilitate transfer of knowledge, experience, and expertise within 
the network to ensure common practices.   All GAW participants will abide by the
WMO policies and the QA/SAC procedures and methodologies to produce data bases 
of consistent and known quality.   Although the country supporting the GAW site 
remains the primary owner of its sites' data and may release them as agreed with 
WMO, the data can only be accepted as GAW data after completing the quality 
assurance/quality control (QA/QC) procedures for GAW.   While the QA/SACs 
perform a network-wide quality review, the site Principal Scientist (PI)[PI = Principal Investigator] 
has primary responsibility for the quality of the data generated at his/her site.
   The QA/SACs will help establish and foster research ties among site PIs and with 
users of GAW data bases to ensure relevance to international scientific and policy concerns.
<P>

The QA/SACs will be advised by a policy advisory board of neutral experts and 
technical advisory groups which include site PIs.   The QA/SAC is envisaged as a 
small core of people who establish short-term of experts to perform the majority 
of functions.   The effectiveness of the QA programme and QA/SAC procedures will be 
reviewed by WMO on regular bases.   An interim review of the QA/SAC system shall 
be conducted by members of the policy advisory board to identify necessary 
corrective actions one year after operation commences.
<P><P>

<H3><B>Specific Duties of QA/SACs</B></H3>
<P>

A regional QA/SAC should in general be responsible for only the sites within its 
own region.
<BR>
The specific duties include:
<P>

<UL>
 <LI>Management of Preparation of QA Plans for Environmental Variables
<OL>
  <LI>ensure the production of specifications for DQOs, QAPjPs, lists of supporting
  <LI>information to be supplied, and the corresponding protocols for flags
  <LI>perform pilot studies to test QA procedures in a limited scale before full
  <LI>implementation
  <LI>coordinate activities among all QA/SACs
</OL>
<BR><BR>

 <LI>QA Support
<OL>
  <LI>design and lead QC tests in consultation with sites to resolve performance questions
  <LI>prepare (or identify existing) QA/QC and data-transfer protocols
  <LI>prepare QC activity schedule; site-visit, expert consultations (performance and system audits),
 calibrations, and intercomparisons
  <LI>promote twinning arrangements between sites.   The duties of twins should be elaborated by the QA/SACs.
   Once twinning arrangements have been formalized by WMO, the QA/SAC has the responsibility to implement
 (and monitor) the twinning arrangements
  <LI>identify source of standards and instructions for usage (provide if necessary)
  <LI>periodically review site adequacy (in specific situations, QA activities may be delegated to
 appropriate expert groups outside the GAW network)
  <LI>QA/SAC responsibility to from audit teams.   Audit teams to be constructed from authorities
 in the field of measurement, including personnel of successful GAW sites
  <LI>a total management system audit must be performed at regular frequency, covering data flow
 management from the GAW site to the data centres, to identify effectiveness of the data flow.
</OL>
<BR><BR>

 <LI>Management Review of Data and QC Products
<OL>
  <LI>perform quality checks on data streams and QA products (primary quality checks must be performed by the site PI.)
  <LI>transmit data, metdata, and flags to data centre following review within about 15 working days
  <LI>if review has not occurred within specified time, transmit data, metdata, and flags to data centre with a flag indicating that review has been delayed
  <LI>until QA procedures are fully implemented, all data, metdata and flags will pass through the QA/SAC with flags where appropriate, indicating that the QA/SAC has not review a part of the data because the QA procedure for that part has not been elaborated.   During initiation of the QA/SAC, interim arrangements should be put in place allowing parallel data flows to the QA/SAC and the data centre for a specified period of time (length of time at discretion of QA/SAC) to ensure the effectiveness of the new QA.SAC procedures.   There should be a flag indicating this situation
  <LI>the QA/SAC will take phased approach in the introduction of QA procedures for specific variables, and the inclusion of regional sites
  <LI>allocate station performance categories.
</OL>
<BR><BR>

 <LI>Training
<OL>
  <LI>develop an ongoing, network-specific educational programme
  <LI>prepare development plans for technical personnel and certification procedures to ensure that personnel involved in station operations are properly trained.
</OL>
<BR><BR>

 <LI> Communication and Dissemination of Information
<OL>
  <LI>establish a communications network (e.g., e-mail)
  <LI>promote awareness of technological changes
  <LI>arrange periodic review meeting (including scientists, technicians, and operators from GAW and other scientists whose work is of relevance to GAW) to present scientists, exchange technical information, and facilitate coordination of QA procedures
  <LI>cooperate with international scientific programmes involved in atmospheric research such as the International Global Atmospheric Chemistry Programme (IGBP-IGAC).
</OL>
</UL>

<BR><BR><BR>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER="10">
<TR><TD>
