<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Role of the JMA
</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
The Role of the Japan Meteorological Agency
</P></H1>
<HR SIZE=5>
<BR>

<UL>

<LI>      <FONT SIZE=+2>E</FONT>ven before the establishment of the World Meteorological Organization's World Climate Program (WCP),
the Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA), other related agencies and universities started the significant parts
of on-going programs of climate observations, monitoring, prediction and research.   We summarize the Japan
Meteorological Agency's activities and describe perspectives in the future.
<P>

<LI>      <FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he JMA's Climate Program is being conducted based on "Guidelines for Promotion of the Climate Program"
issued in June, 1981 and "Basic Plan for Climate Research" in April, 1982, which were established in response
to the WCP; the program is being coordinated within the framework of international cooperations involving
observation and monitoring, research, and information exchange related to climate change.
<P><P><P><P>

<LI><H3><I>
Observations
</I></H3>

      <FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he most important elements in climate observations are the regular surface observations such as temperature
and precipitation, the oceanographic observations such as sea water temperature and sea level.   Japan's observations
are well coordinated with the WMO's World Weather Watch (WWW) program, the Integrated Global Ocean Services
System (IGOSS), and Global Sea-Level Observing System (GLOSS).   In addition, as part of the WMO's Global Atmosphere
Watch (GAW), Japan carries out observations of background levels of atmospheric greenhouse gases and ozone-depleting
substances and the ozone layer and harmful ultraviolet rays.   Japan has played a leading role of oceanographic
observations of greenhouse gases as well as other substances in the sea surface air and in seawater by means of
regular surveys by research vessels in the northwestern Pacific.
<P><P><P>

<LI><H3><I>
Climate data
</I></H3>

      <FONT SIZE=+2>F</FONT>or over one hundred years, the JMA has been collecting and archiving climate data.   In June 1990,
Japan Climatic Data Center (JCDC) was established to play the role of WMO's Data Centre for Greenhouse Gases (WDCGG);
the JCDC collects and archives global data on carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases and is building a global data base
in other to analyze long-term greenhouse gas trends.   Data and results of their analyses are disseminated international
through data report, data catalogue, data summaries, etc.
<P><P><P>

<LI><H3><I>
Climate monitoring
</I></H3>

      <FONT SIZE=+2>M</FONT>onthly Report on Climate System" have been published since 1987, and the El Ni&ntilde;o Monitoring Center which was
established to strengthen the monitoring and prediction of changes in the ocean climate, particularly in the tropical
Pacific, has published the "El Ni&ntilde;o Monitoring Report" and "JMA Monthly Ocean Report" since April 1992.   As part of the
agency's efforts to step up its observations and monitoring of the global environment in response to recent concerns about
global warning, ozone depletion and other climate changes, the "Annual Report of Ozone Layer Monitoring" has been published
since 1990 and "Monitoring of Global Warning and Ozone Depletion", annually since 1992.   These provide information on the
concentrations of greenhouse gases and their effects on global warning, climate change trends, and the condition of the ozone
layer.
<P><P><P>

<LI><H3><I>
Research
</I></H3>

      <FONT SIZE=+2>V</FONT>arious researches are being carried out in coordination with the World Climate Research Programme (WCRP) and other
international cooperative research programs; researches on clouds and radiations, oceanic variations, processes in
the carbon cycle, the mechanisms of El Ni&ntilde;o events and global warning and their prediction using coupled ocean-atmosphere
general circulation models, ozone depletion, acid precipitation, desertification, etc.   Especially with regard to the global
warning issue of public concern, progress is being made in developing coupled atmosphere-ocean general circulation climate
models for achieving more reliable predictions.   In coordination with the IPCC's activities, climate prediction experiments
are being carried out to simulate transient climate responses to gradually increasing concentrations of carbon dioxide.

</UL>

<HR SIZE=10>
