<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>
JCDC - Global Warming due to Greenhouse Gases
</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY>
<H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
Global Warming due to Greenhouse Gases
</P></H2>
<HR SIZE=5>

<B>
<H3>
The greenhouse Effect
</H3></B>
<BR>

<PRE>
        <FONT SIZE=+2>G</FONT>reenhouse Gases including carbon dioxide (CO<SUB>2</SUB>), methane (CH<SUB>4</SUB>), chlorofluorocarbons
   (CFCs), nitrous oxide (N<SUB>2</SUB>O) and ozone (O<SUB>3</SUB>) allow the solar radiation to penetrate the
   Earth's atmosphere but absorb and re-emit infrared radiation from the Earth.   They thus
   trap heat and cause warm to the surface and the troposphere of the Earth.   With the
   development in human activities, atmospheric concentrations of carbon dioxide and
   other greenhouse gases have been rising year after year, and it is feared that global
   warming will rapidly accelerate.
</PRE>
<BR><BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="GlobalWarm.gif">
</P><BR><BR>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
(IPCC, 1990)</P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=5>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TH></TH><TD>Surface Pressure<BR>(Relative to Earth)</TD><TD>Main Greenhouse Gases</TD><TD>Surface temperature<BR>in<BR>absence of Greenhouse effect</TD><TD>Observed<BR>Surface Temperature</TD><TD>Warming due to<BR>Greenhouse Effect</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TH>VENUS</TH><TD>90</TD><TD>>90% CO<SUB>2</SUB></TD><TD>-46&#176;C</TD><TD>477&#176;C</TD><TD>523&#176;C</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TH>EARTH</TH><TD>1</TD><TD>~0.04% CO<SUB>2</SUB><BR>~1% H<SUB>2</SUB>0</TD><TD>-18&#176;C</TD><TD>15&#176;C</TD><TD>33&#176;C</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TH>MARS</TH><TD>0.007</TD><TD>>80% CO2</TD><TD>-57&#176;C</TD><TD>-47&#176;C</TD><TD>10&#176;C</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>
<BR><BR><BR>



<B>
<H3>
Increase in Atmospheric Concentrations of Carbon Dioxide
</H3></B>
<BR>

<PRE>
        <FONT SIZE=+2>C</FONT>arbon dioxide (CO<SUB>2</SUB>) is one of the most important greenhouse gases.   Until the
   industrial revolution, atmospheric concentration of CO<SUB>2</SUB> was between 270 and 280ppmv
   (parts per million by volume), but since then, because of the increasing use of fossil fuels,
   the concentration has increased remarkably.

        <FONT SIZE=+2>O</FONT>n the occasion of the International Geophysical Year in 1958, continuous modern
   measurement of atmospheric carbon dioxide concentration began at Mauna Loa in
   Hawaii and at the South Pole.   Under the framework of the Global Atmosphere Watch
   (GAW) of the  World Meteorological Organization (WMO), CO<SUB>2</SUB> levels are now observed
   globally at about 60 locations; including two in Japan: Ryori (since 1987), northern part of
   Japan, and Minamitorishima Island (since 1993), isolated in the western north Pacific.

        <FONT SIZE=+2>V</FONT>alues for carbon dioxide concentrations before 1957 are obtained by analyzing air bubbles
   trapped in ice cores in Antarctica, etc.

        <FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he carbon dioxide concentration data observed over many years at Mauna Loa, South
   Pole, Ryori, and other observatories show clearly that carbon dioxide are increasing year
   after year with seasonal variations.   The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change
   (IPCC) established by WMO and the United Environmental Programme (UNEP) estimates the globally
   averaged carbon dioxide concentration in 1992 to be about 355ppmv and the annual growth rate
   to be about 1.5ppmv (about 0.4% per year).
</PRE>
<BR><BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/jcdc/GreenhouseGases/MaunaSouthRyori/MaunaSouthRyori-e.gif">
</P>
<BR>

