<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WDCGG - Trends of Teriberka Monthly Mean CO2
</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H1>
<IMG SRC="/wdcgg/SiteLocation/TeriberkaLocation.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE>
Teriberka Station, Russia
</H1></CENTER>
<BR><BR>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
Covering period : April 1988 - March 1994
</P>
<HR>

<PRE>
<B>Station</B>   : Teriberka               <B>Country/Trretory</B> : Russia                   <B>Submmited by</B> : Main Geophygical Observatory
<B>Latitude</B>  : 69&#176; 12&#180; N               <B>Time Interval</B>    : By Event                 <B>Analysis</B>     : NDIR
<B>Longitude</B> : 35&#176; 06&#180; E               <B>Unit</B>             : ppmv                     <B>Calibration</B>  : SIO X87 Mole Fraction Scale
<B>Altitude</B>  : 40 m                    <B>Classification</B>   : Provisional
</PRE>
<BR><BR>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER="10">
<TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="Teriberka-CO2.gif">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>
<BR><BR>

<PRE>
<B>Authors      :</B> A. Shashkov, N. Paramonova, V. Privalov, Y. Starodubtzev

<B>Organization :</B> Main Geophysical Observatory

<B>Address      :</B> Karbyshev Street 7, St. Petersburg, 194018 Russia

<B>Site Position and description :</B>
   69&#176; 12&#180; N, 35&#176; 07&#180; E, 15 msl, arctic coastal seashore

<B>Sampling method, frequency and measurements technique :</B>
   Samples were collected into stainless steel flasks of 1.5l, with electro-polished inner walls, four
   times per month, and subsequently analyzed by NDIR in Leningrad.

<B>Scientific aims and scope of measurements :</B> Monitor atmospheric CO<SUB>2</SUB> increase

<B>Data selection procedures used for daily values :</B>
        Numbers in the body of table are the monthly mean values, calculated on the base of daily mean
   values, selected as follows:
        The daily mean values are the averages for two CO<SUB>2</SUB> concentrations, measured in two simultaneously
   sampled flasks, if difference between these measured concentration value is less or equal 1 ppmv.
   Otherwise, lower of two measured value is included in the table as a daily value if it does not
   differ from the smoothed concentration curve for more than 2 standard deviations.  Those "single value
   data" are flagged in accordance with the convention, accepted at the WDCGG manual.  Technically
   invalid data were also removed.
        All accepted data for the samples with the water vapor partial pressure e>2.2mbar.   Were corrected
   for storage time, using the experimental formula:

                dC=-(0.0023<SUP>*</SUP>e-0.005)<SUP>*</SUP>t,

   where dC-is an additive correction to the measured concentration values, e-is water vapor partial pressure
   in the air sample (mb), and t-is storage time for a sample: from sampling to analyses date.  Samples with
   less humidity were not subjected to any correction at all.

<B>Calibration gases used :</B>
        CO2-in-synthetic air reference gases were primarily used for calibration.   Those gases were
   initially calibrated at the Scripps Institution of Oceanography in 1981.   The CO<SUB>2</SUB> concentration values in
   this set cover the range 318-354 ppmv.
        In 1990-1993 the calibration experiments were performed by us, using the set of 5 CO<SUB>2</SUB>-in-air
   tertiary gas standards provided by the Atmospheric Environment Service of Canada.  In 1990-1993 all
   our data were recalculated according the results of these calibrations.

<B>Scale of reported data :</B> SIO X87 mole fraction scale.

<B>Acknowledgment :</B>
        We are grateful to the sincere help in our work Dr. Shchukin - the Director of Scientific Research
   Remote Sensing Center, Dr. Neil Trivett of the Atmospheric Environment Service of Canada, Dr. J.
   Miller of WMO, the Central European University of George Soros Foundation and the international CO<SUB>2</SUB>
   society for kind patronage of our work.


</PRE>
<B>
<HR SIZE=5><HR SIZE=5 WIDTH=80%>
