<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WDCGG - Trends of Mace Head Monthly Mean CH4
</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H1>
<IMG SRC="/wdcgg/SiteLocation/MaceHead-NOAALocation.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE>
Mace Head Station, Ireland
</H1></CENTER>
<BR><BR>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
Covering period : June 1991 - December 1993
</P>
<HR>

<PRE>
<B>Station</B>   : Mace Head                 <B>Country/Trretory</B> : Ireland                  <B>Submmited by</B> : NOAA/CMDL
<B>Latitude</B>  : 53&#176; 20&#180; N                 <B>Time Interval</B>    : By Event                 <B>Analysis</B>     : GC-FID
<B>Longitude</B> : 09&#176; 54&#180; W                 <B>Unit</B>             : ppbv                     <B>Calibration</B>  : Gravimetric Standard
<B>Altitude</B>  : 25 m                      <B>Classification</B>   : Provisional              <B>Facility</B>     : University College Atmospheric Research Station (AEROCE)
</PRE>
<BR><BR>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER="10">
<TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="MaceHeadNoaa-CH4.gif">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>
<BR><BR>

<PRE>
     The following is an explanatory note, though a little modified, cited by the WDCGG from the
explanatory note of the NOAA Flask Network.

     NOAA/CMDL has attempted to provide the most accurate and precise measurements possible in
a timely manner.   We reserve the right to adjust the data based on recalibrations of reference gases
and instruments.   In particular, the data for calendar year 1991 are preliminary and are subject to
possibly significant modifications.   Thirty six of the land-based sites were active 1992.   Sampling
at Ocean Station C was discontinued in 1973, and at St. Croix sampling was discontinued in 1990.  
Also included are data from three shipboard flask sampling programs.   Samples are collected at
approximately 5-degree latitude intervals on regular cruises of the Southland Star and Wellington
Star in the Pacific Ocean between the west coast of the U.S. and New Zealand.   For Southland
Star and Wellington Star, the sampling frequency in each latitude bin is insufficient to calculate
monthly means.   Samples are also collected at 3-degree latitude intervals aboard the Carla A. Hill
on regular cruises in the South China Sea between Hong Kong and Singapore.   The Monthly
means are produced for each site by first averaging all values in the complete file with a unique
sample data and time.   These data are fit with a curve (see <I>Steele et al.</I>, 1992 for curve fitting
techniques), values are pulled from the curve at weekly intervals, and these values are averaged for
each month to give the monthly mean values in the files.

== REFERENCES ==
Lang, P.M., L.P. Steele, R.C. Martin and K.A.Masarie, 1990a: Atmospheric methane data for the period
    1983-1985 from the NOAA/GMCC global cooperative flask sampling network.
    <I>NOAA Tech. Memo. ERL CMDL-1</I>, NOAA ERL, Boulder, Colorado, 90pp.
Lang, P.M., L.P. Steele and R.C. Martin, 1990b: Atmospheric methane data for the period 1986-1988 from
    the NOAA/CMDL global cooperative flask sampling network. <I>NOAA Tech. Memo. ERL CMDL-2</I>, NOAA ERL,
    Boulder, Colorado, 108pp.
Lang, P.M., L.P. Steele, L.S. Waterman, R.C. Martin, K.A. Masarie and E.J. Dlugokencky, 1992:
    NOAA/CMDL atmospheric methane data for the period 1983-1990 from shipboard flask sampling. <I>NOAA Tech.
    Memo. ERL CMDL-4</I>, NOAA ERL, Boulder, Colorado, 88pp.
Steele, L.P., P.J. Fraser, R.A. Rasmussen, M.A.K. Khalil, T.J. Conway, A.J. Crawford, R.H. Gammon, K.A. Masarie
    and K.W. Thoning, 1987: The global distribution of methane in the troposphere. <I>J. Atmos. Chem,</I> 5, 125-171.
Steele, L.P. and P.M. Lang, 1991: Atmospheric methane concentrations-the NOAA/CMDL global cooperative
    flask sampling network, 19983-19988, ORNL/CDIAC-42, NDP-038.
Steele, L.P., E.J. Dlugokencky, P.M. Lang, P.P. Tans, R.C. Martin and K.A. Masarie, 1992: Slowing down
    of the global accumulation of atmospheric methane during the 1980's,. <I>Nature</I>, 358, 313.


</PRE>
