</ol>
<hr width=95% size =1>
<ol type=1>
<a name="B"> </a>
<li><strong>What services does GCRIO provide for its users?</strong>
<p align=left>
The GCRIO offers the following products and services to its users:
<p align=left>
<ul>
<li>GCRIO acts as a clearinghouse for key documents and reports generated or sponsored by the U.S. Government or selected Federal Agencies that pertain to global change research, adaptation/mitigation strategies and technologies, and global change related educational resources.  GCRIO generates abstracts of these documents and places them into an on-line, searchable bibliographic data base.  GCRIO also provides links to other Agency and commercial bibliographic systems.  Selected documents are placed on-line in their entirety.</li>
<p>
<li>GCRIO provides high-level User Services for the interagency <a href="http://www.gcdis.usgcrp.gov/">Global Change Data and Information System</a> (GCDIS).  The function is designed to complement the existing User Support functions already in place at the various Federal Agencies.  Requests for data and information from GCDIS are processed by <a href=#Z>GCRIO User Services</a>  staff and, if necessary, forwarded to the appropriate Agency contact.</li>
<p>
<li>GCRIO performs outreach services to both domestic (Federal, state, and local) and international target audiences (including governments, institutions, researchers, educators, students, and the general public) in an effort to showcase relevant activities and results of the US Global Change Research Program and to help increase the awareness of the availability of data and information resources of the participating Federal Agencies.</li>
<p>
<li>The <a href="http://www.gcrio.org">GCRIO Home Page</a> provides access to selected  bibliographic data bases; web sites at the participating Federal Agencies; relevant environmental data, catalog, and library systems; and a special section that deals with environmental education and research funding opportunities.  Brochures describing GCRIO's products and services are available in English, French, Russian, Spanish, Arabic, and Chinese.</li>

</li>
</ol>
<hr width=95% size=1 >
<a name="C"> </a>
<p align=left><li><strong>What is in the GCRIO On-line Bibliographic Data Base?</strong>
<p align=left>
Information on documents and publications relevant to the GCRIO mission(providing access to data and information on global change research, adaptation/mitigation strategies and technologies, and global change related educational resources) has been requested from each of the agencies and organizations participating in the <a href="http://www.usgcrp.gov">US Global Change Research Program(USGCRP)</a> GCRIO staff abstracted these documents and placed the descriptions into an on-line data base.  In addition to brief abstracts, each data base record contains information on the format of the document, the agency of origin, and a list of related keywords that assist in free-text searches. 
<p>
In some cases, the agency or organization provided multiple copies of the document or publication to GCRIO so that the <a href=#Z>GCRIO User Services</a>  could respond to user requests directly.  In other cases, the agency or organization provided only one copy for abstraction purposes, and requests for those documents are forwarded by GCRIO User Services to the appropriate agency or organization for disposition.   
<p align=left>
The population of this on-line bibliographic data base is an on-going task.  Please note that the various Federal Agency and Organizations participate in this effort on a volunteer basis.  Thus, the robustness of the data base is dependent upon our ability to encourage and facilitate participation.  Another factor is that many Agencies and Organization expend considerable effort in maintaining their own bibliographic data bases.  GCRIO does not intend to duplicate these existing agency services.  Instead, GCRIO offers its users the ability to link to other relevant bibliographic data bases from its Document Search Home Page
<p>
Other private or non-governmental organizations are invited to provide copies relevant materials to the GCRIO User Services for possible inclusion in the GCRIO bibliographic on-line data base.  Contact the <a href=#Z>GCRIO User Services</a>  for details.
</li>
<hr width=95% size=1>
<a name="D"> </a>
<p align=left><li><strong>How do I order a document from GCRIO?</strong>
<p align=left>
In general, users may obtain a copy of a document that is described in 
the GCRIO on-line bibliographic data base free of charge.  Please provide your name, address, telephone, fax, email information, plus the title and/or ID number of the document(s) that you wish to order to either of the following offices:
<p>
<a name="Z"> </a>

<table border>
<tr>
<td>
GCRIO User Services</td><td> +1-517-797-2730 (tel)</td><tr>
<td> 2250 Pierce Road</td><td> +1-517-797-6622 (fax)</td><tr>
<td> University Center, MI  48710 USA</td><td><a href = "mailto:help@gcrio.org">help@gcrio.org</a></td>
</table>

<p>
<p>GCRIO Director<br> 
<p>

<table border>
<tr>
<td>
Carroll A. Hood</td><td> +1-202-775-6607 (tel)</td><tr>
<td> 1747 Pennsylvania Ave., N.W., Suite 200</td><td> +1-202-775-6622 (fax)</td><tr>
<td> Washington, DC 20006 USA</td><td><a href = "mailto:chood@gcrio.org">chood@gcrio.org</a></td>
</table>

<p>Most orders are processed within one or two business days and are either mailed out first class or forwarded to an appropriate Agency for follow-up.  Multiple copies or overseas distribution will be mailed at the most economic rate.</li>
<hr width=95% size=1>
<a name="E"></a> 
<p align=left><li> <strong>Does the GCRIO have a list of publications or a catalog?</strong>
<p align=left>
You may request a list of titles and abstracts of the GCRIO document holdings directly from the GCRIO Document Search Home Page or you may request from <a href=#Z>GCRIO User Services</a> that a list of titles and abstracts be sent, free of charge, by postal mail, email or fax.
</li>
<hr width=95% size=1>
<a name="F"> </a>
<p align=left><li><strong>What about on-line documents?</strong>
<p align=left>
GCRIO provides selected key documents on-line in full-text.  The selection for on-line placement is usually made of the basis of importance to the USGCRP (i.e., the annual production of <i>Our Changing Planet</i>), timeliness (i.e., the recent National Academy review of the USGCRP and NASA's MTPE), or need to disseminate new scientific findings.
<p>
Organizations or individuals wishing to place a complete document within the GCRIO web space may contact the <a href=#Z>GCRIO User Services</a> to obtain submission guidelines and selection criteria.
</li>
<hr width=95% size=1>
<a name="G"> </a>
<p><li><strong>What is the difference between GCDIS & GCRIO?</strong>
<p align=left>
The <a href="http://www.gcdis.usgcrp.gov"> Global Change Data and Information System (GCDIS)</a> provides access to the global change related data and information sources and services of the participating Federal agencies through organized Internet-accessible interfaces.   The GCRIO supports GCDIS through provision of User Services and Outreach services.
<p>
<h3>GCDIS Overview</h3>
<p>
The GCDIS is the set of individual agency data and information systems supplemented by a minimal amount of crosscutting new infrastructure, and made interoperable by the use of standards, common approaches, technology sharing, and data policy coordination.  The GCDIS user community extends from global change researchers to other researchers, policy makers, educators, private industry, and private citizens.  Through the GCDIS, these users are able to learn about the existence and location of relevant data and information resources, have key holding available in useful forms, and be assured of their quality and continued availability.
<p>
The individual agency components of the GCDIS are funded through their respective budgets.  There will neither be a lead agency nor a separately funded budget for the GCDIS.  Interagency GCDIS implementation will be coordinated through the GCDIS Subgroup of the Data Management Working Group (DMWG) of  the Subcommittee of Global Change Research (SGCR). 
<p>
<h3>GCRIO Support of GCDIS User Services and Outreach</h3>  
The GCDIS Implementation Plan (1994) states that the User Support and Outreach function applies to all agencies (or their designees) participating in the GCDIS access system at any level.  Common elements include:
<p align=left>
<ul>
<li>Provision of expert staff personnel to assist users with GCDIS access system functions;</li>
<li>Use of information outreach to users of products and services;</li>
<li>Mechanism for obtaining and responding to user feedback;</li>
<li>Ability to exchange information with User Service elements of other agencies/organizations.</li>
</ul>
<p align=left>
GCRIO has defined an approach to User Services and Outreach that complements that functionality without duplicating any existing agency effort.  Elements of the GCRIO approach include:
<p align=left>
<ul>
<li>Developing and maintaining a <i>GCDIS White Pages </i>, or a directory of people so that GCRIO can act as a switchboard, linking users with the global change related contacts at the relevant Federal Agencies or Organizations; 
   </li>
<li>Developing and maintaining a <i>GCDIS Yellow Pages</i>, or a directory of services so that GCRIO can act as a switchboard linking users with the global change-related functions or services at the relevant Federal Agencies or Organizations; </li>
<li>Providing access and links to relevant global change related documentation generated and maintained by the various Federal Agencies or Organizations; </li>
<li>Facilitating access to relevant global change-related data and information products generated and maintained by the various Federal Agencies or Organizations; </li>
<li>Representing GCDIS at selected, relevant national and international meetings and fora;</li>
<li>Promoting a GCDIS Speaker's Bureau in an effort to match user requirements for speakers on global change topics and issues, with appropriate agency contacts. </li>
</ul>
<hr width=95% size=1>
<a name="H"></a>
<p align=left><li><strong>Does GCRIO provide reference/research(journal articles, research reports, books, etc.) to researchers or scholars?</strong>
<p align=left>The GCRIO does not provide in-depth research services but serves more in the referral role and as the provider of on-line access to information systems and resources  via computer networks.</li>
<hr width=95% size=1>
<a name="I"></a>
<p align=left><li><strong>We are students working on the relationship between the "greenhouse effects" and the sea level rise.  Can the GCRIO help us?</strong>
<p align=left>Please feel free to contact the GCRIO for assistance.  The exponential growth of information resources often makes it very difficult to know where to find relevant information. 
<p>The <a href=#Z>GCRIO User Services</a> tries to find the best and most direct resource by selecting and organizing many resources from experts and agencies involved in global environmental change information and the integration of librarians, and researchers, provides a real value-added service that will guide users with specific information needs.<br></li> 
<p>The following GCRIO links are particularly relevant to your topic:<br>
<p><a href="/EPA/sealevel/seatitle.html">The Probability of Sea Level Rise</a>, an EPA report, develops probability-based projections that can be added to local
tide-gauge trends to estimate future sea level at particular locations.  A hard
copy may also be obtained from the EPA by faxing a request to (513) 489-8695, or
 writing to:<br>

National Center for Environmental Publications and Information<br>
P.O. Box 42419<br>
Cincinatti, OH   4524<br>
<p>The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change(IPCC) Second Assessment Report</a> will be published(mid 1996).  The IPCC has made the Synthesis Report, and the Summaries for Policymakers for all three working groups, available for on-line reading and downloading from the <a href="http://www.unep.ch/ipcc/ipcc95.html">United Nations Environment Program</a>. To purchase a hardbound copy, please contact:<br>
Cambridge University Press<br>
40 West 20th Street<br>
New York, NY 10011-4211<br>
Fax:  (212) 691-3239<br>
<hr width=95% size=1>
<a name="J"> </a>
<p align=left><li><strong>I need stratospheric data for the amount of NO2 and O3 present prior to the eruption of Mt. Pinatubo in 1991 and the measurements after the eruption.  Could you supply the data requested or direct us to an alternative source accessible on the internet?</a></strong>
<p align=left>Two articles in Our Changing Planet include references to your topic:<br>
<p>Grant, W.B. et al.  JOURNAL OF GEOPHYSICAL RESEARCH."Aerosol-Associated
Changes in Tropical Stratospheric Ozone Following the Eruption of Mount
Pinatubo."  Vol. 99, pp.8197-8211, 1994.
<p>Data on tropical ozone amounts taken before and after the Mt. Pinatubo
eruption(June 1991) show that there were significant decreases in lower
stratospheric ozone in the year following the eruption.  By comparing
ozone measuremetns take from airborne lidar and balloon ozonesondes
during September 1991 and May-August, 1992 with sonde and satellite data
taken previously, these changes were quantified.  In September, 1991, thereduction in the 16-28 km region was some 33% (29+-Dobson Units, DU) from
pre-Pinatubo amounts.  Comparable changes(33+-7 DU) were observed in the
summer of 1992.
<p>Hilsenrath, E. et al.  JOURNAL OF GEOPHYSICAL RESEARCH.  "Calibaration of
the NOAA 11 Solar Backscatter Ultra Violet (SBUV/2) Ozone Data Set from 1989
to 1993 Using Inflight Calibration Data and SSBUV."  Vol. 100,
p.1351-1366, 1995.
<p>The longest satellite-base ozone data set ever assembled has been created
by combining observations from NASA's Solar Backscatter Ultraviolet
Radiometer (SBUV) and NOAA's SBUV/2.  The merged global data set covers
the period 1978 to 1994 and is being used to evaluate global ozone
trends.  The data set of ozone vertical distribution obtained by the
Solar Backscatter Ultraviol (SBUV/2) instrument on the NOAA-11
operational meteorological satellite was reprocessed, leading the to the
currently available version(Version 6) data set.

<p>2)  Two Internet sites you will want to check out:

<p>ATMOSPHERIC CHEMISTRY OZONE MEASUREMENTS
[http://daac.gsfc.nasa.gov/CAMPAIGN_DOCS/ATM_CHEM/ozone_measurements.html]<br>
<dt>This site includes:
<dd>Measurement of Atmospheric Ozone
<dd>Ground Based Measurements
<dd>Airborne Measurements
<dd>Satellite Measurements</dt>
<p>Mentions "measuring ozone from the bottom of the stratosphere to
the top of the atmosphere with a vertical resolution of 3km. Besides
ozone, LIMS observed other parameters that influence ozone chemistry: water
vapor, NO2, HNO3, and temperature."<br>
<p>LANGLEY RESEARCH CENTER<br>
URL:  http://eosdis.larc.nasa.gov/HBDOCS/LARC.html<br>
<p>Stratospheric Aerosol and Gas Experiment(SAGE) data appears to be the best
source of data for your request.<br>

<p>You may contact them directly:
<dt>
<dd>Langley DAAC User and Data Services
<dd>Mail Stop 157D
<dd>NASA Langley Research Center
<dd>Hampton, VA 23681-0001
<dd>Telephone: (804) 864-8656
<dd>FAX: (804) 864-8807
<dd>Internet: larc@eos.nasa.gov</dt></li>
<hr width=95% size=1>
<a name="K"> </a>
<p><li><strong>Can the GCRIO supply any materials for teachers?</strong>
<p align=left>
Teachers with on-line connections may access the GCRIO Home Page for 
global change-related lesson plans, listservers, resource guides, and program brochures; information on education awards & grants; and other useful education resources.  Teachers without on-line access may request educational resources by contacting <a hr

ef=#Z>GCRIO User Services</a> by mail, phone or fax.
</li>
<hr width=95% size=1>
<a name="L"> </a>
<p align=left><li><strong>Does GCRIO provide any services for users without on-line access?</strong>
<p align=left>
<a href=#Z>GCRIO User Services</a> responds to requests by mail, phone or fax and can provide documents, referrals, etc. 
</li>
<hr width=95% size=1>
<a name="M"> </a>
<p align=left><li><strong>Acronyms!!  Yipes, there are so many!!  Can GCRIO help?</strong>
<p align=left>
The GCRIO maintains a list of <a href="http://www.gcrio.org/gcacronyms.html">Global Change Acronyms 
and 
Abbreviations</a>.  You may print a copy directly from the GCRIO World Wide Web site or request a print copy, free of charge from <a href=#Z>GCRIO User Services</a></
li>.
<hr width=95% size=1>
<a name="N"> </a>
